yle data-emotion-css="jlixm8-LongExplainerBase">.css-jlixm8-LongExplainerBase{border:solid 0.0625rem #aeaeb5;border-top:none;padding:0.5rem 0.5rem 0 0.5rem;}</style><div class="css-jlixm8-LongExplainerBase e1pqeqp65"><style data-emotion-css="15a41bl-LongExplainerParagraph">.css-15a41bl-LongExplainerParagraph{margin:0 0 0.5rem 0;padding:0;}</style><p class="css-15a41bl-LongExplainerParagraph e1pqeqp64">The BBC is now projecting that Joe Biden will take Wisconsin, in line with our US sister network CBS.</p><p class="css-15a41bl-LongExplainerParagraph e1pqeqp64">With 99% of the votes counted, Biden currently has a lead there of just over 20,000 on Donald Trump. The tally above now includes the state’s 10 electoral college votes.</p><p class="css-15a41bl-LongExplainerParagraph e1pqeqp64">Our results maps, however, do not show Wisconsin for Biden. This is because they’re driven by data, supplied via Reuters, from polling firm Edison Research.</p><p class="css-15a41bl-LongExplainerParagraph e1pqeqp64">It has not projected a result for Wisconsin because the margin between Biden and Trump is less than one percentage point, meaning a candidate can request a recount.</p><p class="css-15a41bl-LongExplainerParagraph e1pqeqp64">Our projection that Joe Biden is the presumptive winner in Wisconsin reflects the situation now. If a recount takes place, we will report that and the result - and if necessary, we’ll change our projections accordingly.</p><p class="css-15a41bl-LongExplainerParagraph e1pqeqp64">You may have noticed that some other news sites are also projecting a win in Arizona for Biden, giving him an extra 11 electoral college votes. The BBC, again in line with CBS, considers the state too early to project.</p><p class="css-15a41bl-LongExplainerParagraph e1pqeqp64">With 86% of the vote in Arizona counted, Biden currently has a lead of about 68,000 over Trump.</p></div></details><style data-emotion-css="xl31k-LinksContainer">.css-xl31k-LinksContainer{font-size:0.9375rem;